SIMPLE: neat
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Neat
<hw>Neat</hw> <pr>(n⟦emac⟧t)</pr>, <pos>n. sing. & pl.</pos> <ety>[AS.
<ets>ne⟦aacute⟧t</ets>; akin to OHG. <ets>n⟦omac⟧z</ets>, Icel.
<ets>naut</ets>, Sw. <ets>n⟦oum⟧t</ets>, Dan. <ets>n⟦oum⟧d</ets>, and to
AS. <ets>ne⟦oacute⟧tan</ets> to make use of, G. <ets>geniessen</ets>,
Goth. <ets>niutan</ets> to have a share in, have joy of, Lith.
<ets>nauda</ets> use, profit.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Cattle of
the genus <gen>Bos</gen>, as distinguished from horses, sheep, and
goats; an animal of the genus <gen>Bos</gen>; <as>as, a <ex>neat's</ex>
tongue; a <ex>neat's</ex> foot.</as></def>
<rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Wherein the herds[men] were keeping of their <qex>neat</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The steer, the heifer, and the calf⟦br⟧
Are all called <qex>neat</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A <qex>neat</qex> and a sheep of his own.</q>
<rj><qau>Tusser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Neat's-foot</b></col>, <cd>an oil obtained by boiling the
feet of neat cattle. It is used to render leather soft and
pliable.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Neat</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Neat
<hw>Neat</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[See <er>neat</er>,
<pos>n.</pos>]</ety> <def>Of or pertaining to the genus <gen>Bos</gen>,
or to cattle of that genus; <as>as, <ex>neat</ex> cattle</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Neat</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Neat
<hw>Neat</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <amorph>[<pos>Compar.</pos>
<adjf>Neater</adjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>superl.</pos>
<adjf>Neatest</adjf>.]</amorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>nett</ets>, F.
<ets>nett</ets>, fr. L. <ets>nitidus</ets>, fr. <ets>nitere</ets> to
shine. Cf. <er>Nitid</er>, <er>Net</er>, <pos>a.</pos>,
<er>Natty</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Free from that which soils,
defiles, or disorders; clean; cleanly; tidy.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>If you were to see her, you would wonder what poor body it was
that was so surprisingly <qex>neat</qex> and clean.</q>
<rj><qau>Law.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Free from what is unbecoming, inappropriate, or
tawdry; simple and becoming; pleasing with simplicity; tasteful; chaste;
<as>as, a <ex>neat</ex> style; a <ex>neat</ex> dress.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Free from admixture or adulteration; good of its
kind; <as>as, <ex>neat</ex> brandy; to drink one's vodka
<ex>neat</ex></as>.</def> <specif>Hence:</specif> <fld>(Chem.)</fld>
<def>Pure; undiluted; <as>as, dissolved in <ex>neat</ex>
acetone</as>.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧Our old wine <xex>neat</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Chapman.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Excellent in character, skill, or performance, etc.;
nice; finished; adroit; <as>as, a <ex>neat</ex> design; a <ex>neat</ex>
thief.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>With all deductions or allowances made; net.
<note>[In this sense usually written <asp>net</asp>. See <er>Net</er>,
<pos>a.</pos>, 3.]</note></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>neat line</b></col> <fld>(Civil Engin.)</fld>, <cd>a line
to which work is to be built or formed.</cd> -- <col><b>Neat
work</b></col>, <cd>work built or formed to neat lines.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Nice; pure; cleanly; tidy; trim;
spruce.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>'Neath</ent>⟦br⟧
